1. Income

  1. Describe in detail the features you observe in the boxplots below, plotted with data from the ex0525 dataset, Sleuth3 page. (see page 29 in Graphical Data Analysis in R for a list of features to concentrate on, and the numbered list on the bottom of page 43 for an example of how to describe features of a graph in words.) [5 points]
  1. There are few people with income more than $100,000.
  2. The higher the education level, the more income people will have.
  3. There is no clear outliers in group <12 comparing to all other groups.
  4. There is one extreme outlier in group >16.
#install.packages("Sleuth3")
library(Sleuth3)
library(tidyverse)

# convert Educ from an integer to a factor, and make "<12" the first factor level 
mydata <- ex0525 %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(Educ = forcats::fct_relevel(Educ, "<12"))
ggplot(mydata, aes(Educ, Income2005)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()   # for horizontal boxplots

  1. Plot a histogram of the Income2005 variable in the dataset referenced in part a). [3 points]
library(ggplot2)
#ggplot(mydata, aes(x = Income2005)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Income2005), binwidth = 2350) + xlim(0,705000) + xlab("Income2005") + ggtitle("Histogram of Income2005")
Income2005 = mydata$Income2005
df <- data.frame(Income2005)
ggplot(df, aes(Income2005)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 10000) + xlab("Income of 2005") + ggtitle("Histogram of Income of 2005")

  1. Use +facet_wrap(~Educ) to facet the histogram on education level. [3 points]
ggplot(mydata, aes(x = Income2005)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 10000) + xlab("Income2005") + ggtitle("Histogram of Income 2005 ") + facet_wrap(~Educ)

  1. What do you learn from the histograms that wasnt apparent in the boxplots from question 1? [3 points]

I can see from the histograms where the mode of the income distribution of each education level lies roughly. Histograms can also tell us the count of different income level, whereas on the boxplot, we can only see the interquatile range.

2. Respiratory Rates

  1. Plot right closed and right open histograms for each of the two variables in the ex0824 dataset in the Sleuth3 package using default binwidths and breaks. (4 histograms in total). [4 points]
library(Sleuth3)
library(ggplot2)
data2 = ex0824

ggplot(data2, aes(Age)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Age), color = "black", fill = "lightblue") + xlab("Age") + ggtitle("Right Open Histogram of Age")

ggplot(data2, aes(Age)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Age), color = "black", fill = "lightblue", right = FALSE) + xlab("Age") + ggtitle("Right Closed Histogram of Age")

ggplot(data2, aes(Rate)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Rate), color = "black", fill = "lightyellow") + xlab("Rate") + ggtitle("Right Open Histogram of Rate")

ggplot(data2, aes(Rate)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Rate), color = "black", fill = "lightyellow", right = FALSE) + xlab("Rate") + ggtitle("Right Closed Histogram of Rate")

  1. For which variable, Age or Rate, do the two versions differ more? Why? [3 points]

The two versions of the Rate variable differ more since the two Rate histograms clearly look different on bin heights on the two graphs. On the other hand, the two Age histograms almost look identical except that there might be very slight variations in the plots.

  1. Redraw the Age histograms with different parameters so that the right closed and right open versions are identical. [3 points]
ggplot(data2, aes(Age)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Age), color = "black", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 1.51) + xlab("Age") + ggtitle("Right Open Histogram of Age")

ggplot(data2, aes(Age)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = Age), color = "black", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 1.51, right = FALSE) + xlab("Age") + ggtitle("Right Closed Histogram of Age")

3. Movie budgets

Are there rounding patterns in the budget variable of the movies in the ggplot2movies package? If so, what are the patterns? (Note: according to the textbook this dataset is in the ggplot2 package, but it has since been moved to a separate package.) Support your conclusions with graphical evidence. You are encouraged to break the variable down into different budget ranges and consider them separately. [8 points]

Form the histograms below, we can see that for budget under $100,000, most numbers are rounded to the thousand digit and the ten thousand digit. For budget from $100,000 to $10,000,000, most numbers are rounded to ten thousand digit and the hundred thousand digit. For budget more than $10,000,000, most numbers are rounded to the one million digitand the ten million digit.

library(ggplot2movies)
library(ggplot2)

data3 = movies
Budget = data3$budget
bg <- Budget[!is.na(Budget)]
sortedbg = sort(bg, decreasing = FALSE)
range1 = data.frame(sortedbg[which(sortedbg < 100000)])
range2 = data.frame(sortedbg[which((sortedbg >= 100000) & (sortedbg < 10000000))]) #10w & 1w
range3 = data.frame(sortedbg[which(sortedbg >= 10000000)]) #100w
zero1 = c(sum(range1 %% 10==0)-sum((range1 %% 100) == 0), sum((range1 %% 100) == 0)-sum((range1 %% 1000) == 0),sum((range1 %% 1000) == 0)-sum((range1 %% 10000) == 0), sum((range1 %% 10000) == 0)) 
# 7  75 515 323
zero2 = c(sum(range2 %% 10==0)-sum(range2 %% 100==0), sum(range2 %% 100==0)-sum(range2 %% 1000==0),sum(range2 %% 1000==0)-sum(range2 %% 10000==0), sum(range2 %% 10000==0)-sum(range2 %% 100000==0), sum(range2 %% 100000==0)-sum(range2 %% 1000000==0), sum(range2 %% 1000000==0))
# 17    8  246  354 958 873
zero3 = c(sum(range3 %% 10==0)-sum(range3 %% 100==0), sum(range3 %% 100==0)-sum(range3 %% 1000==0),sum(range3 %% 1000==0)-sum(range3 %% 10000==0), sum(range3 %% 10000==0)-sum(range3 %% 100000==0), sum(range3 %% 100000==0)-sum(range3 %% 1000000==0),sum(range3 %% 1000000==0)-sum(range3 %% 10000000==0), sum(range3 %% 10000000==0)-sum(range3 %% 100000000==0),sum(range3 %% 100000000==0))
# 0    0    0    4   59 1094  575

HundredThousand = data.frame(c(rep(1,7), rep(2,75), rep(3,515), rep(4,323)))
TenMil = data.frame(c(rep(1,17), rep(2,8), rep(3, 246), rep(4, 354), rep(5,958), rep(6,873)))
bil = data.frame(c(rep(4,4),rep(5,59),rep(6,1094), rep(7,578), rep(8, 17)))

ggplot(HundredThousand, aes(HundredThousand)) + geom_histogram(aes(x = HundredThousand), color = "black", fill = "lightblue", binwidth = 1, xlab = "Number of Zeros") + ggtitle("Histogram of Budget under $100,000")

ggplot(TenMil, aes(TenMil))+geom_histogram(aes(x = TenMil), color = "black", fill = "lightyellow", binwidth = 1) + xlab("Number of Zeros")+ ggtitle("Histogram of Budget from $100,000 to $10,000,000")

ggplot(bil, aes(bil))+geom_histogram(aes(x = bil), color = "black", fill = "lightpink", binwidth = 1) + xlab("Number of Zeros") + ggtitle("Histogram of Budget more than $10,000,000")

4. Finches

  1. Plot separate density histograms of the beak depth of the finches in case0201 from the Sleuth3 package, with density curves overlaid as on page 34 of the textbook. (However, do this by facetting on Year rather than using grid.arrange). [3 points]
library(Sleuth3)
data4 = case0201
year = as.factor(data4$Year)
ggplot(data4) +
  geom_histogram(aes(Depth, y=..density..), binwidth=1, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") +facet_wrap(~Year) +
  geom_density(aes(x = Depth, color = year)) + xlim(6, 12) + xlab("Depth") + ylab("") + ggtitle("Depth")

  1. Plot both density curves on the same graph to facilitate comparison. Make 1976 yellow and 1978 blue. Use alpha blending so the fills are transparent. [3 points]
ggplot(data4) +
  geom_density(aes(x = Depth, color = year, fill = year), alpha = 0.4) + xlim(6, 12) + xlab("Depth") + ylab("") + ggtitle("Depth")

  1. Based on your graphs in parts a) and b), describe how the distributions differ by year. [3 points]

From the histograms and density curves, we can clearly see that more data lie within the range from 10 to 12 in year 1978, therefore, the distribution of year 1978 is more skewed to the right. Looking at the density curves in part b), we can also see the mode in 1978 is bigger than the mode in 1976.

  1. What is the cause of the difference according to the information in the help file? [3 points]
help(case0201)

It is very likely that due to the drought in 1977, only birds with larger and stronger beaks could open the tough seeds and survied, thus passing the genes to their offsprings. Therefore, the birds in year 1978 had longer beak depths than the ones in year 1976.

5. Salary

Is the Salary variable in the case0102 of Sleuth3 normally distributed? Use two different graphical methods to provide evidence. [6 points] The Salary data are almost normally distributed. The data points in Q-Qplots are almost lying on the Q-Q line, and the histogram are looking similar to bell shape, but not exactly equal to the bell curve.

library(Sleuth3)
data5 = case0102
Salary = data5$Salary
qqnorm(Salary, main="Salary QQplot", xlab="",ylab="", pch = 16)
qqline(Salary)

library(Sleuth3)
ggplot(data5) +
  geom_histogram(aes(Salary), binwidth=300, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") +
  geom_density(aes(x = Salary))  + xlab("Salary") + ylab("") + ggtitle("Salary Histogram")
